RBI chief batted for ordinary bank customers. More can be done
Indian banks are awash in money. In 2023, they held 103L cr – $1.2tn – in FDs alone. The small customer can seem too small from their vantage. So, kudos to RBI governor Sanjay Malhotra for speaking up for the little guy. On Monday, Malhotra rapped banks for poor customer service. Everybody’s had a taste of it, but data shows the full extent of the rot. Complaints received under RBI’s ombudsman scheme – not resolved by your bank, hence escalated to RBI – have grown at 50% a year for the past two years. If India’s GDP grew that fast, it would overtake US in just over 5 years. That’s why Malhotra called it a “highly unsatisfactory situation” that needs “urgent attention”. He also flagged the underreporting of complaints by banks. In 2023-24, India’s scheduled commercial banks together received over 1cr complaints, but it turns out they were window dressing data – many complaints were listed as requests, queries and disputes, which is a regulatory violation.
In simpler times, banking-related complaints were mostly about forgery and wrong entry, but complexity has broadened the gamut of problems. For example, on Wednesday TOI reported about a man in Gujarat whose credit score fell because of his bank’s mistake, making him ineligible for loans. Bank branches misselling investment schemes and other products like life insurance is another outrage. A few years ago, a report pointed out that bank branches rewarded staff for selling these products but not for better customer service.
Last year, RBI raised concerns about gold loans. In Dec, it cautioned banks about unsecured loans, and top-up loans offered with minimum due diligence. Now, SC has sought a CBI probe into another old problem – the “nexus” between banks and builders due to which lakhs of homebuyers are paying EMIs without any hope of getting their house. As it told counsel for banks on Tuesday: “…knowing not a brick has been laid at the site, you released 60%. How can this be without quid pro quo?” Banks have much to answer, and fix. They should heed Malhotra’s warning: “Left unresolved, such issues can erode consumer confidence and tarnish the entire ecosystem.”
This piece appeared as an editorial opinion in the print edition of The Times of India.
